# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banana-beer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In 2016, UNESCO inscribed Belgian beer culture on their list of the intangible cultural heritage of humanity.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In Belgium, beer was already produced in the Roman era, as evidenced by the excavation of a brewery and malthouse from the 3rd and 4th centuries AD at Ronchinne.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] During the Early and High Middle Ages, beer was produced with gruit, a mix of herbs and spices that was first mentioned in 974 when the bishop of Liège was granted the right to sell it at Fosses-la-Ville.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] From the 14th century onwards, gruit was replaced by hops, after the example of imported beers from northern Germany and Holland.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] After that, several Belgian towns developed their own types of beer for export to other regions, most notably the white beer of Leuven and Hoegaarden, the *caves* of Lier and the *uitzet* of Ghent.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In recent years, the use of gruit has experienced a revival, particularly among homebrewers and eventually by commercial breweries.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] For instance, Gageleer brews a beer using sweet gale (*Myrica gale*) based on a medieval recipe.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Monasteries played only a small role in beer production and mostly brewed for their own consumption and that of their guests.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Monastic brewing would only receive some renown from the late 19th century onwards, when the Trappists of Chimay produced a brown beer that was commercially available.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In 1885, a change in legislation made brewing of German-style bottom-fermenting beers viable in Belgium, and it was only from then that large industrial-scale brewing in Belgium took off.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] During the 20th century the number of breweries in Belgium declined from 3223 breweries in 1900 to only 106 breweries in 1993.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Yet, a number of traditional beer styles, such as white beer, lambic and Flemish old brown were preserved, while new local, top-fermented styles developed, such as *spéciale belge*, abbey beer and Belgian strong ale.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In 1988, the country's two biggest breweries, Artois and Piedboeuf, formally merged to become Interbrew, then the world's 18th biggest brewer, which was to merge with AmBev in 2004 to become today's AB InBev, the biggest beer producing company in the world.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In Belgium, four types of fermentation methods are used for the brewing of beer, which is unique in the world.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a range of colours, brewing methods, and alcohol levels.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Beers brewed in Trappist monasteries are termed Trappist beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] For a beer to qualify for Trappist certification, the brewery must be in a monastery, the monks must play a role in its production and the policies and the profits from the sale must be used to support the monastery or social programs outside.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Only ten monasteries currently meet these qualifications, five of which are in Belgium, two in the Netherlands, one in Austria, one in Italy and one in the United Kingdom.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Trappist beer is a controlled term of origin: it tells where the beers come from, it is not the name of a beer style.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Beyond their being mostly warm fermented, Trappist beers have very little in common stylistically.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In addition to the above, a lower-strength beer is sometimes brewed for consumption by the brothers (*patersbier*) or sold on site.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] For example, *l’Orval Vert* (or *Petit Orval*, also known as "Green Orval" or "Small Orval") is served to the monks and guests of the Orval Abbey and can only be consumed on tap in the nearby *À l’Ange Gardien* abbey café.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The designation "abbey beers" (*Bières d'Abbaye* or *Abdijbier*) originally applied to any monastic or monastic-style beer.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] After introduction of an official Trappist beer designation by the International Trappist Association in 1997, it came to mean products similar in style or presentation to monastic beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The requirements for registration under the logo include the monastery having control over certain aspects of the commercial operation, and a proportion of profits going to the abbey or to its designated charities.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Monastic orders other than the Trappists can be and are included in this arrangement.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The "Abbey beer" logo and quality label is no longer used for beers given the name of a fictitious abbey, a vaguely monastic branding or a saint name without mentioning a specific monastery.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some brewers may produce abbey-style beers such as dubbel or tripel, using such names but will refrain from using the term Abbey beer in their branding.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] What connoisseurs now recognize as Trappist breweries began operations in 1838.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Several monasteries, however, maintained "working" breweries for 500+ years before the French regime disrupted religious life (1795–1799).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Even then, some Abbey beers such as Affligem Abbey, whose name now appears on beers made by the Heineken-owned Affligem Brewery, resumed brewing from "working" monasteries until the occupation of most of Belgium in World War I.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Commercial Abbey beers first appeared during Belgium's World War I recovery.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Although Abbey beers do not conform to rigid brewing styles, most tend to include the most recognizable and distinctive Trappist styles of brune (Belgian brown ale, aka dubbel), strong pale ale or tripel, and blonde ale or blond.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Modern abbey breweries range from microbreweries to international giants, but at least one beer writer warns against assuming that closeness of connection with a real monastery confirms a product's quality.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] This style makes up the bulk of beer production and consumption in Belgium.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Belgian Pilsners are not particularly distinctive or renowned by connoisseurs.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The top brands include Jupiler (within Belgium) and Stella Artois (both brewed by Inbev), Maes pils and Cristal (both brewed by the Alken Maes branch of Heineken).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Stella Artois, originating in Leuven, Belgium; is distributed globally.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The Pilsnerbeer is which is popularly called "*pintje*" (in Flemish, from English "pint" but in volume only 0.25 cl or roughly 1/2 pint) or "*choppe*" (in French) in Belgium, was the basis of the "*fluitjesbier*" distributed during the German occupation in WWII and under rationing.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] This "*fluitjesbier*" was watered down to about 0.8° (compared to fruitjuice which can have up to 1.5° due to natural fermentation).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Bock is a strong lager of German origin.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some Belgian brewers have produced bock-style beers what makes it a style applicable to Belgium.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] This type of beer, commonly called *witbier* in Dutch, *bière blanche* in French and *wheat beer* in English, originated in the Flemish part of Belgium in the Middle Ages.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Traditionally, it is made with a mixture of wheat and barley.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Before hops became widely available in Europe, beers were flavoured with a mixture of herbs called gruit.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In the later years of the Middle Ages, hops were added to the gruit.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] That mixture continues today in most Belgian white beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The production of this type of beer in Belgium had nearly ended by the late 1950s.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In the town of Hoegaarden, the last *witbier* brewery, Tomsin, closed its doors in 1955.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] However, ten years later, a young farmer by the name of Pierre Celis in the same village decided to try reviving the beer.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In 1966, Celis began brewing a "witbier" in his farmhouse.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Ultimately, the Hoegaarden brewery took the name of the village and became successful, gaining international prominence.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] For instance, in 2018, only 8% of the 1.3 million hectoliters of beer produced annually were intended for the Belgian market.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some notable current examples are Celis White, Blanche de Namur and Watou's Wit.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Their alcohol strength is about 5–6 percent ABV, and these beers can be quite refreshing, especially during the warm summer months.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The herb mixture traditionally includes coriander and bitter orange peel, among other herbs.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] White beers also have a moderate light grain sweetness from the wheat used.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In recent times, brewers have been making fruit flavoured wheat beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] These are a light variation on pale ale, often made with pilsner malt.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some beer writers regard blonde and golden ales as distinct styles, while others do not.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Duvel is the archetypal Belgian blonde ale, and one of the most popular bottled beers in the country as well as being well known internationally.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Its name means "Devil" and some other blonde beers follow the theme—Satan, Lucifer and Judas for example.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The style is popular with Walloon brewers, the slightly hazy Moinette being the best-known example.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Chouffe can be considered a spiced version (with coriander).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A few Belgian beers are pale and assertively hopped.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] De Ranke's XX Bitter has a British-style name.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Arabier from De Dolle Brouwers.Brouwerij Van Eecke's Poperings Hommelbier, another example, hails from Belgium's hop-growing district.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] From Lambic four kinds of beer are produced: Lambic, Gueuze, Fruit Lambic, and Faro.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] These are beers similar to the traditional pale ales of England, although less bitterly hopped.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A notable example is the 5% ABV De Koninck brand, with its distinctive half-spherical glasses (called 'bollekes').
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] It is popular in its native city of Antwerp.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some, such as Vieux Temps, were based on British styles to please troops stationed in Belgium during World War I.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Others were introduced by the UK-born brewer George Maw Johnson in the late 19th century.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A very strong *ambrée* is brewed by "Bush" (*Dubuisson*), another brewery influenced by British styles.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Walloon amber or *ambrée* ale, such a Gauloise Ambrée, is considered to be somewhat distinct by some beer writers, and to be influenced by the French version of the *ambrée* style.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Tripel is a term used originally by brewers in the Low Countries to describe a strong pale ale, and became associated with *Westmalle Tripel*.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The style of Westmalle's *Tripel* and the name was widely copied by the breweries of Belgium, then the term spread to the US and other countries.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] *Gulden Draak* was awarded the best-tasting beer in the world in 1998 by the *American Tasting Institute* (now ChefsBest).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Dubbel (*double*) has a characteristic brown colour.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] It is one of the classic Abbey/Trappist types, having been developed in the 19th century at the Trappist monastery in Westmalle.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Today, some commercial brewers using abbey names call their strong brown beers "Dubbel".
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Typically, a dubbel is between 6 and 8% abv.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In addition to the dubbels made by most Trappist breweries, examples include St.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Bernardus Pater, Adelardus Dubbel, Maredsous 8 and Witkap Dubbel.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Dubbels are characteristically bottle conditioned.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The result is a mildly strong 'drinking' beer with a deep reddish-brown colour and a distinctly acidic, sour yet fruity and mouthy taste.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] This style is closely related to Oud bruin.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] This style, aged in wooden casks, is a cousin to the sour "Flemish Red" style.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Rodenbach, Goudenband and Petrus.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Regular bruin or brune beers such as Grottenbier are darker than amber ales, less sour than Flemish brown ale, and less strong than dubbel.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] These sweet, heavy-bodied brown ales represent a style which originated in the British Isles.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The Caledonian theme is usually heavily emphasized with tartan and thistles appearing on labels.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Gordon's, Scotch de Silly and La Chouffe Mc Chouffe.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Belgian stouts subdivide into sweeter and drier, and stronger and weaker versions.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Callewaerts and Ellezelloise Hercule.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The sweeter versions resemble the almost-defunct British style "milk stout", while the stronger ones are sometimes described as Imperial stouts.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Champagne style beers are generally ales that are finished "à la méthode originale" for champagne.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Examples include Grottenbier, DeuS and Malheur Bière Brut.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] They receive a second fermentation much like Champagne does and are stored for several months "sûr lie" while the fermentation lasts.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] This creates the smaller, softer bubbles that we know from Champagne, but maintains the beer flavour and style.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In Belgium "Grand Cru" is more often used than "Quadrupel", these beers are a mostly a blend of brews, which is often refermented as a blend.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Saison (French for "season") is the name originally given to refreshing, low-alcohol beers brewed seasonally in Wallonia, the French-speaking region of Belgium.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] First seen in early 19th century Liège, saisons gained notoriety as a luxury beer in 20th century Hainaut brewed by city and countryside brewers alike.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] By the 1980s, they were only produced on the countryside.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Modern-day saisons are also brewed in other countries, particularly USA, and are generally bottle conditioned, with an average range of 5 to 8% ABV, though saisons at the more traditional 3.5% strength can still be found.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Although saison has been described as an endangered style, there has been a rise in interest in this style in recent years, with Saison Dupont being named "the Best Beer in the World" by the magazine *Men's Journal* in July 2005.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A related style known as a grisette was brewed with a lower ABV and with wheat added.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Many breweries produce special beers during December.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Most contain more alcohol than the brewery's other types of beer and may also contain spicing.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] An annual beer festival in Essen near Antwerp focuses on this type of beer with over 190 beers available for tasting in 2014.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some brewers that are not Lambic-brewers make fruit beers in a similar process as the Fruit Lambic beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] All brewers of this style make fruit lambic.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Many brewers of top fermentation beers such as Belgian golden ales, ambers and Flemish old brown beers, that produce beers that usually go through a multiple stage fermentation process, are catching on to the trend to make fruit beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The process starts after the first fermentation of the wort, when sometimes sugar is added to referment the beer on wooden casks.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] To make fruit beer the fruit, juice or syrup is added (instead of sugar) to the first brew and refermented, these may be termed fruit lambics or fruit beers, depending on the type of first brew.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Beer that has fruit syrup or fruit lemonade added after (the final stage of) fermentation, in other words as a flavouring, are termed "Radlers" ("Shandy" in the UK) definitely not fruit beer.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Beers above 7%, such as tripels or strong dubbels, are referred to in some sources as Belgian strong ale, although this is not a name used by Belgian brewers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Belgian beers have a wide range of styles and brewing methods and are almost always served in unique, branded glassware.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Each glass is designed to enhance the beer’s taste and aroma, often featuring the brewery’s logo or a beer-specific design.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Belgian "heavy" or "special" beers (stronger or bottled beers) are usually served in more elaborate branded beer glassware.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some glasses are etched on the bottom; typically with the brewery’s logo, to nucleate a stream of bubbles for maintaining a nice head.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Unless the bar is out of the specific glass that goes with that beer it is usually served in its own glass.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Most bartenders or waitresses will apologize if the beer comes in a different glass.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Pils (pilsner) or pale lager, remains the most widely produced and consumed beer style in Belgium.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] One of the most typical Belgian pilsner glasses is the ribbed glass, often referred to as the *ribbelke* or *ribbelglas*.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The Belgian pilsner glass originated between 1860 and 1900.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Its ribbed base was designed to minimize heat transfer from the drinker’s hand, preventing the beer from warming.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Additionally, the glass’s tall, narrow, and straight shape is suited to pilsner beers due to their lower foaming protein content, necessitating a smaller diameter to maintain an appropriate head.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A regional variation is the *Boerke* glass, which translates to "small farmer".
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The question of which glass is best suited for Belgian pilsner remains a subject of debate, influenced by factors such as personal preference, brand loyalty, tradition, regional customs, and differing opinions among Belgians.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] One of the more common types is the tulip glass.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A tulip glass not only helps trap the aroma, but also aids in maintaining large heads, creating a visual and olfactory sensation.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The body is bulbous, but the top flares out to form a lip which helps foam head retention.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A vessel similar to a champagne flute is the preferred serving vessel for Belgian (fruit) Lambics, Gueuze and fruit beers.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The narrow shape helps maintain carbonation, while providing a strong aromatic front.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Flute glasses display the lively carbonation, sparkling colour, and soft lacing of this distinct style.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Traditionally, lambic beers including gueuze and fruit lambics are served in a tall glass resembling the ribbed pilsner glass.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] However, the edges and base of the lambic glass are significantly thicker; which originated from the old custom of grinding sugar at the bottom of the glass before serving, allowing drinkers to sweeten the beer to their taste, as lambic styles are known for their intense sourness.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The glass is commonly referred to as a *lambiekstoemper* (or "lambic stomper"), a name that reflects the practice of crushing sugar with a tool similar to a cocktail muddler.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Chalices and goblets are large, stemmed, bowl-shaped glasses mainly associated with Trappist and Abbey ales.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The distinction between goblet and chalice is typically in the glass thickness.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Goblets tend to be more delicate and thin, while the chalice is heavy and thick walled.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] However, a more recent addition, though not traditionally Belgian, is the TeKu beer glass, developed in 2006 by Teo Musso and Kuaska (hence the acronym).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Designed as a universal beer glass, it has since been embraced by the craft beer community, particularly for styles such as pale ales, IPAs, stouts...
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In addition to the profusion of glasses provided by brewers, some Belgian beer cafés serve beer in their own "house" glassware.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The majority of Belgian beer brands are sold in reusable bottles.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Draught beers tend mostly to be pale lagers, wheat beers, regional favourites such as kriek in Brussels or De Koninck in Antwerp; and the occasional one-off.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] These days, Belgian beers are sold in brown- (or sometimes dark green-) tinted glass bottles (to avoid negative effects of light on the beverage) and sealed with a cork, a metal crown cap, or sometimes both.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some beers are bottle conditioned, meaning reseeded with yeast so that an additional fermentation may take place.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Different bottle sizes exist: 25 cl, 33 cl, 37.5 cl, 75 cl and multiples of 75.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] (8, 12, 24 or multiples of 24 fl. oz.) The 37.5 cl size is usually for lambics.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Other beers are generally bottled in 25 or 33 cl format (depending on brands).
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The bigger bottles (75 cl) are sold almost in every food shop but customers do not always have an extensive choice.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Bottles larger than 75 cl are named following the terminology used for champagne and are limited in quantity.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In Brussels or Walloon Belgian cafés, you can order orders a *demi* (English: "half"), which is a 50 cl draught beer.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The prominence of the Belgian beer culture is reflected in the extensive range of beers offered in nearly every café across the country.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Belgium contains thousands of cafés that offer a wide selection of beers, a typical beer menu ranges from at least half a dozen draught beers and two dozen bottled beers of different types in a neighborhood café, to over 1000 in a specialist beer café.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Although many major brands of beer are available at most supermarkets, off-licences located throughout the country generally offer a far wider selection, albeit at somewhat higher prices.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In 2024, Belgium exported around 70% of its beer production, amounting to approximately 14 million hectoliters.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some draught-beer brands produced by AB InBev like Stella Artois, Hoegaarden and Leffe are available in several European countries.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Aside from these, mostly bottled beer is exported across Europe.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Cafés, exclusively or primarily offering Belgian beers, exist beyond Belgium in Australia, New Zealand, Canada, France, the United Kingdom and the United States, amongst others.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Some beer festivals outside Belgium have a Belgian beer bar as an alternative to local products.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In North America, a growing number of draught Belgian beer brands have started to become available, often at "Belgian Bars".
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Such brands include Brasserie Brunehaut, Karmeliet, Kwak, Maredsous, Mont Saint-Aubert, Delirium, Palm, Rodenbach and St.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] A number of traditional Belgian dishes use beer as an ingredient.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] One is *carbonade* (French) or *stoverij* or *stoofvlees* (Dutch), a stew of beef cooked in beer, similar to Boeuf bourguignon.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The beer used is typically the regional speciality—lambic in Brussels, De Koninck in Antwerp, and so on—so that the taste of the dish varies.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] *In't Spinnekopke*, Brussels, and *Den Dyver*, Bruges are famed for their beer cookery.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] In 1998 Anheuser-Busch InBev started a worldwide chain of bars/restaurants, Belgian Beer Cafe, serving typical Belgian dishes combined with Belgian Beer.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Beer writers who have written extensively on Belgian beer include Belgians Peter Crombeq, Gert van Lierde and Erik Verdonck, and Britons Michael Jackson and Tim Webb.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] The following list contains beers that are brewed in Belgium.
[src:banana-beer/abbey-beers] Not to be confused with "Belgian style" beers that are produced in other countries, and may or may not resemble a style that is specific to Belgium.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] In brewing, **adjuncts** are unmalted grains (such as barley, wheat, maize, rice, rye, and oats) or grain products used in brewing beer which supplement the main mash ingredient (such as malted barley).
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] This is often done with the intention of cutting costs, but sometimes also to create an additional feature, such as better foam retention, flavours or nutritional value or additives.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Both solid and liquid adjuncts are commonly used.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Ingredients which are standard for certain beers, such as wheat in a wheat beer, may be termed adjuncts when used in beers which could be made without them — such as adding wheat to a pale ale for the purpose of creating a lasting head.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] The sense here is that the ingredient is additional and strictly unnecessary, though it may be beneficial and attractive.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Under the Bavarian *Reinheitsgebot* purity law it would be considered that an adjunct is *any* beer ingredient other than water, barley, hops, and yeast; this, however, is an antiquated view.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] This purity law originated in 16th-century Germany and did not initially include yeast due to the fact that it had not been discovered yet.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] The term adjunct is often used to refer to corn, rice, oats, unmalted barley and rye.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] The use of ingredients as substitutes for the main starch source is where the term adjunct is most often used.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Adjuncts can be broadly classified according to the physical form in which they are used into solids and liquid syrups.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Barley is used as an un-malted grain at up to 10% of the grist.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Barley provides both carbohydrates and proteins to the wort; on the negative side, the cell walls of the un-malted barley contain high levels of beta-glucans that affect wort viscosity and create haze problems in the bright beer.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Barley is also used in the mash as roasted barley to provide colour to the beer.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Cassava is a novel adjunct used in Africa either as a wet cake or as a purified starch.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Corn is commonly used in the production of American-style pale lagers, particularly malt liquor.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Corn is generally used in brewing as corn syrup, and as such is highly fermentable.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Corn is cheaper than barley, so it is used as a cost-saving measure.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Oatmeal stouts usually do not specifically taste of oats.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] The smoothness of oatmeal stouts comes from the high content of proteins, lipids, and gums imparted by the use of oats.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] The gums increase the viscosity and body adding to the sense of smoothness.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Rice is sometimes used in the production of pale lagers, most notably Anheuser-Busch's Budweiser.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Anheuser-Busch is the largest North American buyer of U.S. rice.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Rice may be used to lighten the body and the mouthfeel, or increase alcohol content, or add a little sweetness.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Rye is used in *roggenbiers* from Germany and in rye beers from America.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Rye is notoriously difficult to brew with, so most rye beers only include a small amount of rye.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Rye provides a spicy flavour to beer and dramatically increases head formation.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Sorghum is used in Africa as a local ingredient saving on expensive imported malt and developing the local agricultural sector.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Sorghum has a high gelatinisation temperature and is added to a mash cooker to gelatinise the starch before adding to the mash tun.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Sorghum has been used for hundreds of years as the main ingredient in many of the indigenous traditional African beers.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Sorghum can be used in the malted or the un-malted form.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Wheat is used in German and American wheat beers, in lambic and other Belgian ales, and in English ales.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Wheat lightens the body, improves head retention, and provides a tart flavour.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Wheat beers are often served with fruit syrups or slices of lemon in the US and Germany.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] In England, beans were occasionally used as an ingredient in beer brewing.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Sugar adjuncts provide only carbohydrates and if used at high levels will result in wort lacking in amino acids and this may lead to poor yeast growth causing tailing fermentations and poor yeast crops.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Primings sugars such as maple syrup, honey, and molasses are common in craft beers and homebrew.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Candi sugar is a common ingredient in strong Belgian ales, where it increases the beer's strength while keeping the body fairly light; dark varieties of candi sugar also affect the colour and flavour of the beer.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Caramel syrup is used to provide colour to brews and can either be added in the wort kettle or at filtration when needed to correct low beer colours.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] This caramel is not sweet and provides little or no fermentable extract.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Honey is a primary fermentable in mead, and can be used for flavour (though also supplying some fermentable sugar) in beer.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Sucrose may come from sugar-cane or from sugar-beet.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] A number of traditional beer styles are brewed with spices.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] For example, Belgian *witbier* and German *gose* are brewed with coriander, Finnish *sahti* is brewed with juniper berries, and traditional beers in Britain are brewed with honey and spices.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Also, some strong winter beers are flavoured with nutmeg or cinnamon, while ginger is a popular flavouring for a range of beers.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Many commercially available pumpkin ales are made with pumpkin pie spices without any actual pumpkin.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Spices may be added to the wort during the boil or spices or spice extract may be added at any time during fermentation depending on desired results.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Other, less common flavourings include chocolate, coffee, milk, chili peppers and even oysters.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Beer may be brewed with a fruit or vegetable adjunct or flavouring.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Fruits have been used as a beer adjunct or flavouring for centuries, especially with Belgian lambic styles.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Cherry, raspberry, and peach are a common addition to this style of beer.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Modern breweries may add only flavoured extracts to the finished product, rather than actually fermenting the fruit.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Pumpkin-flavoured beers are brewed seasonally in the autumn in North America.
[src:banana-beer/adjuncts] Chile pepper is used to flavour pale lagers.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:banana-beer/alcoholic-beverage] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:banana-beer/ale] As with most beers, ale typically has a bittering agent to balance the malt and act as a preservative.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Ale was originally bittered with gruit, a mixture of herbs or spices boiled in the wort before fermentation, before hops replaced gruit as the bittering agent.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In England, however, it was also common to brew ale without adding herbs.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The word *ale* comes into English from its ancestor-language, Proto-Germanic.
[src:banana-beer/ale] English belongs to the West Germanic branch of Proto-Germanic, and some other languages in this branch also attest to the word: Middle Dutch *āle* and *ael*, and the Old Saxon word *alo-fat* 'ale-cup'.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The word is also found throughout the North Germanic languages, almost certainly appearing in ancient runic inscriptions in the form *alu*, and subsequently in Old Norse as *ǫl*.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Through linguistic reconstruction it is possible to infer that the Common Germanic form of this word was **alúþ-*.
[src:banana-beer/ale] According to the third edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*, however, the origin of this word is 'uncertain and disputed'.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Research by Harald Bjorvand, however, has favoured the following explanation: the Germanic word **alú-þ-* descends from the Indo-European word ***olú-t-* (from an earlier Indo-European base **h₂elut-*), which originally meant 'golden or reddish colour'.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Other Indo-European words related to this root include Old Indic *aruṣá-* ('reddish'; the *r* comes from an earlier *l*, **alu-sá-*) and Old High German *elo* ('yellowy, pale yellow, reddish yellow, tawny').
[src:banana-beer/ale] The Indo-European word **olú-t-* then came to refer specifically to ale because this is its colour, giving rise to both the Germanic word **alú-þ-* and the Ossetic word *æluton*.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In this account, the Indo-European word **olú-t-* was also borrowed into the Finnic languages, giving Finnish *olut* and Estonian *õlu*.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The relationship of similar words in the Slavonic languages (such as Old Bulgarian *olu* 'cider', Slovenian *ol* 'beer') and the Baltic languages (Lithuanian *alus*, Latvian *alus*, 'beer', Old Prussian *alu* 'mead') remains uncertain.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Ale was an important source of nutrition in the medieval world.
[src:banana-beer/ale] It was one of three main sources of grain in the diet at the start of the fourteenth century in England, along with pottage and bread.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Scholars believe grains accounted for around 80% of the calorie intake of agricultural workers and 75% for soldiers - even nobles received around 65% of their calories from grains.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Small beer, also known as table beer or mild beer, which was highly nutritious, contained just enough alcohol to act as a preservative, and provided hydration without intoxicating effects.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Small beer would have been consumed daily by almost everyone, including children, in the medieval world, with higher-alcohol ales served for recreational purposes.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The lower cost for proprietors combined with the lower taxes levied on small beer inevitably led to the selling of some beer labeled "strong beer" that had actually been diluted with small beer.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Records from the Middle Ages show that ale was consumed in huge quantities.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In 1272, a husband and wife who retired at Selby Abbey were given 2 gallons of ale per day with two loaves of white bread and one loaf of brown bread.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Monks at Westminster Abbey consumed 1 gallon of ale each day.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In 1299, Henry de Lacy's household purchased an average of 85 gallons of ale daily and in 1385–86 Framlingham Castle consumed 78 gallons per day.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Brewing ale in the Middle Ages was a local industry primarily pursued by women.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Brewsters, or alewives, would brew in the home for both domestic consumption and small scale commercial sale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Brewsters provided a substantial supplemental income for families; however, only in select few cases, as was the case for widows, was brewing considered the primary income of the household.
[src:banana-beer/ale] From the mid-17th century, strong ales became particularly fashionable.
[src:banana-beer/ale] They were known by names such as Huff-Cap, Nippitate and Hum-Cup, so called because it caused "a humming sensation in the head".
[src:banana-beer/ale] Strong ale, like wine, was typically decanted due to the high sediment content into small glasses, which were better suited to the high ABV ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Modern ale is typically fermented at temperatures between 15 and 24 °C (59 and 75 °F).
[src:banana-beer/ale] At temperatures above 24 °C (75 °F) the yeast can produce significant amounts of esters and other secondary flavour and aroma products, and the result is often a beer with slightly "fruity" compounds resembling those found in fruits, such as apple, pear, pineapple, banana, plum, cherry, or prune.
[src:banana-beer/ale] When ale ferments, it naturally creates two prevalent byproducts, those being Sulfur Dioxide (SO2) and Hydrogen Sulfide (H2S).
[src:banana-beer/ale] Each of these compounds affects the product in different ways, and each can be managed before and during the fermenting process to create different flavours and benefits for the ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Sulfur Dioxide is a product of some of the initial ingredients of ale and is produced during the fermentation of the wort.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Sulfur Dioxide helps to increase an ale's shelf life; however, it naturally occurs in foods when they become old, so many people react negatively to its smell and can even be viewed as an allergen in some countries.
[src:banana-beer/ale] During the stages of fermentation of ale, the production of SO2 works as an antioxidant, a preservative, and, in addition, it works to fight bacteria.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Throughout the fermentation process, one of the ways in which brewers can control the levels of SO2 is through temperature during brewing, and another way to preserve that reaction is by tempering with the temperature at which the product is stored.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The cooler it is stored, the more SO2 is preserved, which helps the ale keep its flavour.
[src:banana-beer/ale] When an ale becomes stale from oxidation, it loses its natural flavours; it could taste like any multitude of different undesirable things, depending on the initial flavour of the ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Some of the most common tastes for people are that of sherry, where the flavours have gotten negatively sweeter, or that of cardboard or paper, where it tastes stale and bland.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Hydrogen sulfide is another byproduct of fermentation.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In yeast strains, it helps the yeast grow and also works as an antioxidant later in the fermentation process.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Having a chemical compound including sulfur, however, means that it has a pungent smell that people often associate with rotten eggs, which can later affect the produced ale negatively, so producing and managing a finite amount of hydrogen sulfide is very important in the fermenting of ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] When controlled, the amount of H2S is generally unnoticeable and does not affect the overall smell or taste, but still does its job of keeping the shelf life of the ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] While making ale, sugar can be added either during the boiling stage or the fermenting stage; however, both times lead to similar outcomes, just at different levels of effectiveness.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The benefits of adding sugar to a brew can be to increase the overall APV levels of the brew and the flavour at the end of the brewing process.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Due to the higher APV, however, the body of the beer can often be left thinner, having a water-like consistency.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Both the factors of APV levels and flavour depend on what type of sugar you are adding, and oftentimes, when you add them in the process.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Generally, the later a sugar is added to the brew, the more prominent the flavour will be.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Sugar can be added so long as it is fermentable, which most common sugars are.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Generally, brewers will add different syrups, saps, honeys, and syrups to their ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Flocculation is the tendency for the yeast to conglomerate into large masses at the top and bottom of the fermentation tank at the end of the fermentation process.
[src:banana-beer/ale] This selective trait in the yeast came about as the majority of the yeast that gets repurposed is that which aggregates and gets easily removed.
[src:banana-beer/ale] This selective trait is gradually characterized in most yeast as the yeast that exhibits this behavior lasts a greater number of generations.
[src:banana-beer/ale] "Real ale" is a British term, coined by the Campaign for Real Ale, for cask and bottle-conditioned beer.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The following list breaks the many various ales into separate, diverse categories.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ales listed are categorized into their respective style groups of origin and accompanied by information regarding the specific brew.
[src:banana-beer/ale] For further classification, more comprehensive information can be found in the Brewers Association Style Guide.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In 18th-century England, brewers coined the term "pale ale" to distinguish this golden-hued ale from the more prevalent dark ales of the time.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The use of hops during fermentation introduces a distinctive bitter aroma, while the general absence of diacetyl groups and the presence of esters contribute to a sweeter and fruitier flavour compared to other ales.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The average alcohol by volume (ABV) of these ales ranges from 3.2% to 5.3%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Scotch ale, also known as "wee heavy", boasts an exceptionally malty taste accented by sweet malty undertones due to the heavy concentration of esters.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Generally low in bitterness, it exhibits a deep caramel colour, the shade of which may vary depending on the brewing techniques.
[src:banana-beer/ale] They have a relatively high ABV, falling between 6.6% and 8.5%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] British-style summer ale is characteristically lighter in gold colour.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Filled with esters, this beer yields a fruity flavour and maintains a subdued yet weak profile in bitterness and hop.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ale is traditionally high in carbonation due to its respective brewing techniques.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Falling within the standard ABV range of 3.7% to 5.1% aligns with most beer's typical potency.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Old ale is classified as an intensely dark red ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] It is said to have a fruity aroma, with brewers occasionally adding caramel to sweeten the product.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The hop flavouring and bitterness of an old ale are relatively low compared to other types of categorized ales.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Adequately brewing an old ale involves an aging process spanning a few years.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Upon completion, it yields an extremely sweet drink comparable to wine.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The final ABV of the ale ranges from 5.0% to 9.3%, with higher percentages correlating to the amount of sugar added during fermentation.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Brown ale, distinguished by its dark hue, is commonly enriched with a blend of roasted and caramel malts, leading to a distinctively unique toffee-flavoured ale.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Both esters and diacetyl are found in low levels, contributing to the beer's unique taste.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ABV of brown ales typically ranges between 4.2% and 6.0%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Barley wine is known for its balance of flavour and high alcohol content.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ale's colour varies widely depending on the duration of its age, as its flavour profile evolves dramatically over time.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Low levels of diacetyl and carbonation are found in all barely wines, while esters are found in high quantities, contributing to a low bitter fruity flavour and aroma.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The flavours of barley wines are diverse, ranging from bread-like to hints of molasses and toffee.
[src:banana-beer/ale] They have an unusually high ABV, ranging from 8.5% to 12.2%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] India pale ale, commonly shortened to IPA, is a hoppy pale ale which was originally shipped to colonial India.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Its high hop content prevented spoilage during the long sea course from England to India.
[src:banana-beer/ale] IPA is full bodied and hoppy, it is amber coloured and usually somewhat opaque.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ABV of IPA can fall within the range of 4.5–20%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Amber ale is an American craft beer named after the hue it possesses from being flavoured using caramel malt.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ale is brewed with an assortment of hops and has a balanced flavour.
[src:banana-beer/ale] It maintains a low level of esters and lacks any trace of diacetyl, leading to a moderately bitter and slightly fruity undertone.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ABV of amber ales ranges anywhere from 4.4% to 5.4%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Sour ale, more commonly known as wild ale, is characterized by a unique sour flavour, produced during fermentation when acid-producing bacteria like lactobacillus or acetobacter feed on sugars.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The acidity produced comes from mild concentrations of lactic or acetic acid and further develops during the aging process.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Utilizing wooden bourbon barrels imbued with either vanillin or sherry plays a crucial role in augmenting the beer's flavour complexity during aging.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The presence of esters and diacetyl fluctuates depending on the sought-after flavour profile of the brew.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The final ABV varies widely depending on the length and methods used during brewing.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Table beer typically has a low ABV of around 0.5% - 2.0%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Popular in Eastern Europe, these beverages are brewed with malt barley, wheat, oats, or rye.
[src:banana-beer/ale] They are commonly flavoured with additive sugar and either orange or lemon peels to yield a citrus-like flavouring.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Session ale, named for its purpose of being enjoyed within a single "session" without inducing significant intoxication, features a low ABV, typically ranging from 3% to 5%.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Though they share similarities with table beers, they maintain a higher alcohol percentage.
[src:banana-beer/ale] They are characterized by a balanced flavour profile, as the production method does not stray far from traditional ale brewing.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Esters may be present in medium quantities adding sweetness to the final flavour, while diacetyl is non-existent.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Most commercially available ales fall under the distinction of session ales due to their cost-effective ability to be brewed in mass.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The flavour profile of dark ale is characterized by a malty sweetness resulting from the abundance of esters in the brew.
[src:banana-beer/ale] A discernible spiciness is attributed to yeast-derived phenolic compounds present in moderate quantities.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Depending on the brand, the beer tends to have a modest level of bitterness owing to the hops during fermentation.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The aroma of the brew is described as subtle yet persistent, due to phenol compounds.
[src:banana-beer/ale] In terms of ABV, dark ale ranks notably high compared to other brews, ranging from 7.1% to 11.2%, often veiled by its diverse flavour profile.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Bière de Garde is a hybrid beer whose name translates from French to English as “Beer for Keeping”.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ale is low to moderate in esters and contains a similar malt sweetness to most other ales.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ale's ABV ranges from 4.4% to 8% and has a range of appearances, with its primary descriptions being “Light Amber, Chestnut Brown, or Red.” While most popular in France, this style has become much more frequent in the U.S. as the ale industry grows.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Irish red ale is characterized by its definitive amber or dark red hue, having an ABV ranging from 4.0% to 4.8%, and having a standard approachable bitterness, all of which make this ale highly sessionable.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Medium flavours of candy-like caramel malt distinguish the ale, and a tan foam forms at the top, due to the inclusion of roasted barley.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Originating in the Düsseldorf region of Germany, Altbier pays homage to traditional brewing methods, with "alt" meaning old in English.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The complexion ranges from light amber to a deep copper colour.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Esters are present in low quantities, which is attributed to their lightly citrus profile, while diacetyls are completely absent.
[src:banana-beer/ale] The ale boasts a moderate level of bitterness owing to hops utilized in fermentation.
[src:banana-beer/ale] Its ultimate ABV falls within the range of 4.6% to 5.6%, aligning typically with other ales.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Fried plantain is also eaten in some countries in South America and the Caribbean where African influence is present.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] For example in the Dominican Republic, Nicaragua, Puerto Rico and to a lesser extent Cuba, it is common to cut plantains into slices, fry them until they are yellow, smash them between two plates and fry them again.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Puerto Rico has *mofongo*, a dish consisting of fried and pounded plantains with *chicharrón*, spices, fat (butter, lard or olive oil) and usually in a broth or served with meat, seafood on top or on the side.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] This is also a common dish in Haiti, referred to as *bannann peze*, and throughout Central America, referred to as *patacones* in Costa Rica, Panama, Colombia and Ecuador, and as *tostones* in Nicaragua and the Spanish-speaking Caribbean.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] In Honduras and Venezuela they are referred to as *tajadas*.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Puerto Rico also has *arañitas* (spiders), where green and yellow plantains are shredded together, seasoned, shaped into patties then fried until crisp.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Other traditional fried plantain dishes in Puerto Rico include *alcapurria*, *pionono*, *ralleno de amarillo* (similar to *papa rellena* but made with yellow plantain instead of potato), and *bolitas de plátano* (plantain dumplings).
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Fried plantain may be served as a snack, a starter or a side dish to the main course, such as with Jollof rice, spicy barbecued meat, tomato stew or beans.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] It is made in different ways: salted or unsalted, cut into "ears" or "fingers", diced or fried whole.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] In the Spanish-speaking Caribbean fried green plantains are eaten with mojo sauce in Cuba and Puerto Rico and wasakaka in the Dominican Republic, both a wet savory garlic sauce.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] They are sometimes eaten with ketchup or a mayonnaise-ketchup mixture.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] In the Pacific city of Cali, Colombia, plantains are eaten fried and accompanied by a condiment called Hogao.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Sweet plantains are also served with savory entrees in the Caribbean, especially the Spanish-speaking islands, Pacific Colombia and Jamaica.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Gizdodo is a side dish in Nigeria containing fried plantain and grilled gizzard.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] This traditional snack has a long history and is cherished for its delightful taste and simplicity.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] They are a staple in Yoruba cuisine and is enjoyed by people of all ages across Nigeria.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] To prepare *ipekere*, ripe plantains are peeled and sliced into thin, uniform shapes, typically using a knife or a mandoline slicer.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] These are deep-fried until they turn golden brown, resulting in a crunchy and slightly sweet snack.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] They can also be flavoured with different spices, such as cayenne pepper, ginger, onion powder, or garlic powder.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Some people also fry onions and fresh ginger along with the plantain slices for added flavour.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] The plantains are peeled and may be cut into chunks or cubes.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Ginger, cayenne pepper, and salt are the typical spices used to make *kelewele.* Onions, anise, cloves, nutmeg, cinnamon, and chili powder, however, may also be used as spices.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] Commercial preparations exist that can simplify preparation and offer a standardized taste.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] The oil should be hot and the plantain should not be too soft or it will absorb too much oil.
[src:banana-beer/alloco] The plantain should be fried until the sugar in it caramelizes, and produces brown edges on the plantain.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Altbier is usually a dark, copper colour.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] It is fermented at a moderate temperature using a top-fermenting yeast—which gives its flavour some fruitiness.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Because Altbier is then matured at a cooler temperature, its flavour is more akin to lager beer styles than is the norm for top-fermented beers (such as British pale ale).
[src:banana-beer/altbier] It generally has an ABV between 4.3% and 5.5%.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] The first producer to use the name Altbier—to contrast its top-fermenting beer with the bottom-fermenting kinds—was the Schumacher brewery of Düsseldorf, that opened in 1838.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Mass-market brewers of Altbier include Diebels and the Radeberger Gruppe under the brands Schlösser Alt and Hansa Alt.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] These are complemented by small breweries in Düsseldorf and other nearby cities.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Some Altbier breweries have a tradition of producing a stronger version, called *sticke alt*, coming from a local dialect word meaning "secret".
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Originally made as a special reserve beer intended for the brewers' own consumption, today it is generally a seasonal or special occasion brew.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] There exists a regional rivalry between the drinkers of Altbier in the Düsseldorf area and the drinkers of Kölsch beer in the Cologne (Köln) area.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] A beer variety associated with the Lower Rhine region, Altbier is especially found in Düsseldorf, Krefeld, and Mönchengladbach.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Füchschen, Uerige, Schlüssel and Kürzer are all brewed and sold in the Altstadt (Old Town).
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Schumacher is between the Altstadt and the main train station (Hauptbahnhof), although it also has a pub in the Altstadt, Im Goldenen Kessel, across the street from Schlüssel.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Each brewpub produces a seasonal "Sticke" variant in small quantities, though the names vary: Schlüssel spells it "Stike", without the "c", while Schumacher calls its special beer "Latzenbier", meaning "slat beer", possibly because the kegs from which it was poured had been stored on raised shelves.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Füchschen's seasonal is its Weihnachtsbier (Christmas beer), available in bottles starting mid-November, and served in the brewpub on Christmas Eve.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Altbier is somewhat similar to Cologne's native beer style *Kölsch*, being warm-fermented at a lower temperature than British ales, and Altbier proper is also brewed as "Ehrenfelder Alt", in Cologne's smallest brewery "Braustelle".
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Pinkus Müller brewery in Münster produces an Altbier which is quite different to the Düsseldorf style, being pale and slightly tart.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Altbier has been produced in the city of Venlo in the Netherlands since at least 1753.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Venlo is on the border to Germany approximately 50 km (30 miles) from Düsseldorf.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] The beer was produced up until the Second World War, but then had a hiatus until its revival in 1983.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] It is produced by the Lindeboom brewery, who bought the recipe in 2001.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Altbier is brewed in small quantities in Austria, Switzerland, Hungary, Liechtenstein, the UK, the United States, Canada, Australia by Tooheys in Sydney New South Wales, New Zealand, Japan, South Africa, Norway, Brazil and Australia.
[src:banana-beer/altbier] Versions of altbier are brewed in the United States, though not always to traditional recipes, with Widmer Brothers often considered the first American brewer to produce the style.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Coke had been first used for dry roasting malt in 1642, but it was not until around 1703 that the term *pale ale* was first applied to beers made from such malt.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] By 1784, advertisements appeared in the *Calcutta Gazette* for "light and excellent" pale ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] By 1830, the expressions *bitter* and *pale ale* were synonymous.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Breweries tended to designate beers as "pale ales", though customers would commonly refer to the same beers as "bitters".
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] It is thought that customers used the term *bitter* to differentiate these pale ales from other less noticeably hopped beers such as porters and milds.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Different brewing practices and hop levels have resulted in a range of taste and strength within the pale ale family.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Collier Brothers of London applied for the UK trademark of *The Amber Ale* in 1876 and the trademark was maintained through changes in ownership until it expired in 2002.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] It was a "pure delicately hopped Pale Ale" positioned between their light bitter and IPA.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Since the expiry of the trademark some traditional British bitters have been rebranded as amber ales, in some cases to distinguish them from golden ales sold under the same brand.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Anchor Liberty Ale, a 6% abv ale originally brewed by the Anchor Brewing Company as a special in 1975 to commemorate Paul Revere's "Midnight Ride" in 1775, was seen by Michael Jackson, a writer on beverages, as the first modern American ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The brewery thought to be the first to successfully use significant quantities of American hops in the notably hoppy style of an APA and use the specific name "pale ale" was the Sierra Nevada Brewing Company.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] It brewed the first experimental batch of Sierra Nevada Pale Ale in November 1980, distributing the finished version in March 1981.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Other pioneers of a hoppy American pale ale are Jack McAuliffe of the New Albion Brewing Company and Bert Grant of Yakima Brewing.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] American pale ales are generally around 5% abv, with significant quantities of American hops, typically Cascade.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Although American-brewed beers tend to use a cleaner yeast, and American two row malt, it is the use of strong American hops in particular that distinguish an APA from a British or European pale ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The style is close to the American India pale ale (IPA), and boundaries blur, though IPAs are stronger and more assertively hopped.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The style is also close to amber ale, though these are darker and maltier due to the use of crystal malts.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The origin of the name lies in the tradition that it was matured or cellared for a period of time once bottled (most were sealed with a cork), to be consumed later in the year, akin to a saison.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Among the better French known "*bières de garde*" are Brasserie de Saint-Sylvestre, Trois Monts, Brasseurs Duyck, Jenlain and Brasserie La Choulette, *ambrée*.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The term "blonde" for pale beers is common in Europe and South America – particularly in France, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, the UK, and Brazil – though the beers may not have much in common, other than colour.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Blondes tend to be clear, crisp, and dry, with low-to-medium bitterness and aroma from hops, and some sweetness from malt.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Fruitiness from esters may be perceived.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] A lighter body from higher carbonation may be noticed.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] In the United Kingdom, golden or summer ales were developed in the late 20th century by breweries to compete with the pale lager market.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] A typical golden ale has an appearance and profile similar to that of a pale lager.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Malt character is subdued and the hop profile ranges from spicy to citrus; common hops include Styrian Golding and Cascade.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The UK style is attributed to John Gilbert, owner of Hop Back Brewery, who developed "Summer Lightning" in 1989, which won several awards and inspired numerous imitators.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Belgian blondes are often made with pilsner malt.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Duvel is a typical Belgian blonde ale, and one of the most popular bottled beers in the country as well as being well known internationally.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Burton retained absolute dominance in pale ale brewing until a chemist, C.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Vincent, discovered the process of Burtonization to reproduce the chemical composition of the water from Burton-upon-Trent, thus giving any brewery the capability to brew pale ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The expression *English bitter* first appeared in the early 19th century as part of the development and spread of pale ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] India pale ale (IPA) is a style of pale ale developed in England for export to India.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The first known use of the expression "India pale ale" is in an advertisement in the *Sydney Gazette and New South Wales Advertiser* on 27 August 1829.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Worthington White Shield, originating in Burton-upon-Trent, is a beer considered to be part of the development of India pale ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The colour of an IPA can vary from a light gold to a reddish amber.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The term "Irish red ale" was popularised in the United States and subsequently exported worldwide.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] The additional variants "red ale", "Irish ale" (Irish: *leann dearg*,) and "Irish red", have come to be used by brewers mainly in Ireland and the United States, less so elsewhere.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Smithwick's and Kilkenny are typical examples of macro-brewed commercial Irish red ale.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] There are many other smaller and craft examples, such as O'Hara's, Sullivan's, Murphy's, Porterhouse and Franciscan Well.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Irish red ales are characterised by their malt profile and typically have a sweet, caramel or toffee-like taste, low bitterness and amber to red colour - hence the name.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Irish brewers have increasingly adopted the term Irish Red Ale to distinguish their beers in both the domestic and international markets.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] In the US, the name can also be used simply to describe a darker amber ale, or the abbreviated term "Irish Red" applied to a "reddish" beer brewed as a lager and ambered with caramel colouring - for example Killian's Irish Red.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] Strong pale ales are ales made predominantly with pale malts and have an alcohol strength that may start around 5%, though typically at 7 or 8% by volume, and may go up to 12%, though some brewers have been pushing the alcohol strength higher to produce novelty beers.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] In 1994, the Hair of the Dog Brewing Company produced a strong pale ale with an alcohol by volume of 29%.
[src:banana-beer/amber-ale] In 2010, Brewdog released "Sink the Bismarck!", a 41% abv pale ale, which is stronger than typical U.S. distilled spirits (40% abv).
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] In Uganda, banana beer is known as *mubisi*, in DR Congo as Kasiksi, in Kenya as *urwaga*, and in Rwanda and Burundi as *urwagwa*.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] Banana beer is sometimes consumed during rituals and ceremonies.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] A similar product called *mwenge bigere* is made in Uganda with only bananas and sorghum.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] It can also be found under the names *kasiksi*, *nokrars*, *rwabitoke*, *urwedensiya*, *urwarimu* and *milinda kaki*.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] Banana beer is made from ripe (but not over-ripe) East African Highland bananas (*Musa acuminata* Colla (AAA-EA), *Mbidde* clone set).
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] To accelerate the ripening of bananas, a hole is dug in the ground, lined with dried banana leaves which are then set on fire.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] Fresh banana leaves are laid on top of them, then the unripe bananas.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] These are then covered by more fresh banana leaves and pseudostems.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] After four to six days, the bananas are ripe enough.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] This method only works in the dry season.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] During the rainy season, bananas are ripened by putting them on a hurdle near a cooking fire.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] Two types of banana are used for banana beer: the harsh tasting *igikashi* and the milder tasting *igisahira*.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] The banana beer mixture consists of one third *igikashi* and two thirds *igisahira*.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] They are not ripe enough if they cannot be peeled by hand.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] After peeling, the bananas are kneaded until soft.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] The juice is then filtered to get clear banana juice, which is then diluted with water.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] Sorghum is ground, lightly roasted, and then added to the juice.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] This mixture is left to ferment for 24 hours and then filtered.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] After filtering, the beer is packaged in glass or plastic bottles.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] In commercial production, the beer may first be pasteurized before packaging to stop fermentation and extend shelf life.
[src:banana-beer/banana-beer] Tanzania has a banana beer called mbege, which is still brewed traditionally.
